 colonial Mayan emerged in the age of the cross, how it was taken up by native writers to become the language of indigenous literature, and how it ultimately became the language of rebellion against the system that produced it. Converting Words includes original analyses of the linguistic practices of both missionaries and Mayas-as found in bilingual dictionaries, grammars, catechisms, land documents, native chronicles, petitions, and the forbidden Maya Books of Chilam Balam. Lucidly written and vividly detailed, this important work presents a new approach to the study of religious and cultural conversion that will illuminate the history of Latin America and beyond, and will be essential reading across disciplinary boundaries.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aCatechisms, SpanishzMexicozYucatán (State). 0aCatechisms, Spanish. 0aChristianity and culturezMexicozYucatán (State). 0aChristianity and culturezMexicozYucatán (State). 0aChristianity and other religionszMexicozYucatán (State). 0aChristianity and other religionszMexicozYucatán (State). 0aMaya languagezMexicozYucatán (State)xInfluence on Spanish. 0aMaya languagezMexicozYucatán (State)xInfluence on Spanish. 0aMayasxColonization. 0aMayasxReligion. 0aSpanish languagezMexicozYucatán (State)xInfluence on Maya. 0aSpanish languagezMexicozYucatán (State)xInfluence on Maya. 7aHISTORY / Latin America / General.2bisacsh  aage of the cross.  aanthropology.  abilingual dictionaries.  acatechisms.  achristian missionaries.  achristianity.  acolonial mayans.  acolonialism.  acultural conquest.  acultural conversion.  aforbidden books.  ahistorical.  ahistory of christianity.  aindigenous literature.  alanguage and culture.  alanguage of rebellion.  alatin american history.  alinguistics.  am